11 SECTION 1. ORS 442.615 is amended to read:
12 442.615. (1) As used in this section:
13 (a) “Financial assistance” includes:
14 (A) Charity care, as defined in ORS 442.601; or
15 (B) An adjustment to a patient’s costs for care under ORS 442.614 (1)(a).
16 (b) “Hospital” has the meaning given that term in ORS 442.612.
17 (2) Using the process prescribed by the Oregon Health Authority under subsection (3) of this
18 section, a hospital licensed under ORS 441.025 shall screen a patient for presumptive eligibility for
19 financial assistance if the patient:
20 (a) Is uninsured;
21 (b) Is enrolled in the state medical assistance program; or
22 (c) Owes the hospital more than [$500] $1,500 for a single hospital encounter.
23 (3) The authority shall adopt by rule the process for screening a patient for presumptive eligi-
24 bility for financial assistance under subsection (2) of this section. The rules and process must:
25 (a) Prohibit a hospital from requiring a patient to provide documentation or other verification;
26 (b) Ensure that the process will not cause any negative impact on the patient’s credit score;
27 (c) Require a hospital, before sending a bill to the patient, to conduct the screening and apply
28 any financial assistance for which the patient qualifies to the bill; and
29 (d) Require the hospital to notify a patient if the patient has been screened and to explain to
30 the patient, in language approved by the authority, how to apply for financial assistance if financial
31 assistance was denied, or how to apply for additional financial assistance above what the patient
32 received.
33 (4) A patient may apply for financial assistance:
34 (a) If the patient was screened for presumptive eligibility for financial assistance and was found
35 not to be eligible or the patient disagrees with the amount of the financial assistance that was of-
36 fered;
37 (b) If a patient was not screened for presumptive eligibility for financial assistance; or
38 (c) Any time up to 12 months after a patient pays for the services that the hospital provided.
39 (5) A hospital may require a patient who applies for financial assistance under subsection (4)
40 of this section to provide documentation or verification of information reported as necessary for the
41 hospital to determine the patient’s eligibility for financial assistance.
42 (6) If a patient applies for financial assistance after having paid for the services and the patient
43 is found to have been eligible for financial assistance when the services were provided:
44 (a) The hospital shall refund the amount of financial assistance for which the patient qualified;
45 (b) If the hospital previously determined, incorrectly, that the patient did not qualify for finan-
[2]

