45 SECTION 14. ORS 427.191 is amended to read:
[9]

HB 4040
1 427.191. (1) As used in this section:
2 (a) “Agency” means an agency that hires, trains and supervises direct support professionals us-
3 ing state funds received from the Department of Human Services.
4 (b) “Attendant care services” means services provided directly to an individual with a disability
5 to assist with activities of daily living, instrumental activities of daily living and health-related
6 tasks.
7 (c) “Child” means an individual under 18 years of age who:
8 (A) Has a developmental or intellectual disability; or
9 (B) Meets the eligibility criteria to receive services under the Medically Fragile (Hospital)
10 Model Waiver or the Medically Involved Children’s Waiver approved by the Centers for Medicare
11 and Medicaid Services under 42 U.S.C. 1396n(c).
12 (d) “Client” means an individual who receives attendant care services.
13 (e) “Client child” means a child who receives attendant care services from the child’s parent.
14 (f) “Developmental disability services” has the meaning given that term in ORS 427.101.
15 (g) “Direct support professional” means an individual who is hired, employed, trained, paid and
16 supervised by an agency to provide attendant care services to a client of the agency.
17 (h) “Nonparent caregiver” means a direct support professional, personal support worker or
18 similar provider who is paid to provide attendant care services to clients who are not the provider’s
19 children.
20 (i) “Parent” includes a:
21 (A) Natural or adoptive parent of a child;
22 (B) Stepparent of a child; and
23 (C) Legal guardian of a child.
24 (j)(A) “Parent provider” means a parent who is paid to provide attendant care services to the
25 parent’s minor child.
26 (B) “Parent provider” does not include a parent who is paid to provide attendant care services
27 to a child who is 18 years of age or older.
28 (k)(A) “Personal support worker” means an individual who is employed by a client or the client’s
29 representative and paid to provide attendant care services to the client.
30 (B) “Personal support worker” does not include a direct support professional.
31 (L) “State plan” means Oregon’s state plan for medical assistance, described in 42 U.S.C. 1396a,
32 approved by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services.
33 (m) “Very high behavioral needs” means a minor child’s extraordinary needs for support due to
34 the child’s behavioral condition as indicated by a federally approved functional needs assessment
35 adopted by the department that assigns the child to the highest service level.
36 (n) “Very high medical needs” means a minor child’s extraordinary needs for support due to the
37 child’s medical condition as indicated by a federally approved functional needs assessment adopted
38 by the department that assigns the child to the highest service level.
39 (2) Subject to rules adopted under subsection (8) of this section, to ORS 427.194 and to available
40 funding, the department shall administer a program to compensate parents to provide attendant care
41 services to the parents’ children who have been assessed by the department to have very high
42 medical or very high behavioral needs.
43 (3) To be eligible for the program described in this section:
44 (a) A parent provider must be employed [by an agency and not by the child or the other parent
45 of the child] as a direct support professional or a personal support worker;
[10]

HB 4040
1 (b) The parent provider may not be paid to provide attendant care services to the client child
2 by an agency that is owned by the parent, the client child or any family member or for which the
3 parent or other family member serves in any administrative or leadership capacity, including as a
4 member of a board of directors; and
5 (c) The agency employing the parent provider to provide attendant care services to the client
6 child:
7 (A) May not employ a parent provider as an independent contractor;
8 (B) Shall pay parent providers overtime at the same rate and under the same circumstances as
9 direct support professionals who are not parent providers;
10 (C) Except as authorized by the department by rule, may not pay providers of attendant care
11 services, including parent providers, to provide services to a [minor] child during school hours un-
12 less the [minor] child is temporarily at home recovering from surgery or illness and the temporary
13 absence from school is recommended by the child’s health care provider; and
14 (D) May not pay providers of attendant care services, including parent providers, to provide
15 services to a [minor] child during school hours due to the determination of a school district or due
16 to the choice of a parent of the [client] child to:
17 (i) Have the child regularly attend school less than the number of school hours attended by
18 students without disabilities who are in the same grade and the same school district as the [client]
19 child;
20 (ii) Homeschool the [client] child; or
21 (iii) Enroll the [client] child in a private school that offers fewer school hours than the school
22 hours offered by the local public school to the majority of students in the same grade as the
23 [client] child.
24 (4) Subsection (3)(c)(D) of this section does not prohibit a school district or other entity from
25 compensating parents of students with disabilities for providing support for educational activities
26 that would otherwise be the responsibility of the school district.
27 (5) A parent provider, during the hours that the parent provider is paid to provide one-on-one
28 attendant care services to the client child:
29 (a) May not be responsible for a vulnerable adult who requires physical care and monitoring;
30 (b) May not be responsible for the care of [a child] an individual, other than the client child,
31 who is under 10 years of age and shall have another caregiver immediately available at all times
32 to attend to the needs of the [child] individual; and
33 (c) Unless they are included as a goal or service in the client child’s individual support plan
34 and related to the client child’s disability-related support needs, may not perform tasks that are not
35 for the primary benefit of the client child, including but not limited to:
36 (A) Grocery shopping for the household;
37 (B) Housekeeping not required for the disability-related support needs of the client child;
38 (C) Remote work or operation of a home business; or
39 (D) Transporting individuals other than the client child to or from activities or appointments.
40 (6) If required by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services, the department may require
41 a parent provider to assign an alternative legal representative for the client child to make decisions
42 about or manage the development and implementation of the client child’s individual support plan.
43 The assignment:
44 (a) Must be on a form prescribed by the department; and
45 (b) Must clearly state that the assignment is limited to decisions regarding the development and
[11]

HB 4040
1 implementation of the client child’s individual support plan and does not limit the authority of the
2 parent provider to make decisions for the client child with respect to health care, education or re-
3 ligious training.
4 (7) A parent provider is subject to the requirements of mandatory reporting of abuse under ORS
5 124.060 and 419B.010, 24 hours per day, seven days per week.
6 (8) The department shall adopt rules for the program described in this section using an advisory
7 committee appointed under ORS 183.333 that represents the interests of parents, children with de-
8 velopmental or intellectual disabilities, adults with disabilities, agencies, organizations of direct
9 support professionals and personal support workers and organizations that advocate for persons with
10 disabilities. The rules must include all of the following:
11 (a) Strategies to safeguard nonparent caregivers and avoid the displacement of nonparent
12 caregivers by parent providers;
13 (b) Requirements for agencies to demonstrate consistent efforts to recruit, train and retain
14 nonparent caregivers;
15 (c) Requirements for appropriate training, background checks and oversight, including
16 training requirements for:
17 (A) Parent providers regarding federal and state administrative rules regulating home-based and
18 community-based services, including the impact of the rules on parent-child relationships with re-
19 spect to discipline, supervision, physical intervention and self-determination of client children during
20 the hours that the parent provider is being paid to provide attendant care services;
21 (B) Client children to learn to advocate for themselves with respect to choosing and managing
22 direct support professionals before and after reaching 18 years of age; and
23 (C) Community developmental disability programs related to the employment of parent providers,
24 including on how to support families to manage issues concerning conflicts of interest, provider
25 recruitment and retention and the empowerment of the client child to have a meaningful voice in
26 the selection of the client child’s [direct support professionals] caregivers;
27 (d) A process for a client child to object to the hiring of any caregiver, including the child’s
28 parent, or to raise concerns about a provider’s caregiving;
29 (e) Procedures to ensure that the program described in this section is implemented consistently
30 and equitably throughout this state;
31 (f) A requirement that any appeal related to the requirements of or benefits under the program
32 is the sole responsibility of the central office staff of the department;
33 (g) A requirement that parent providers who are employed as personal support workers
34 are paid comparably to parent providers who are employed as direct support professionals;
35 (h) Procedures to ensure program integrity and prevent duplicate payment for the same
36 service hours; and
37 [(g)] (i) Other requirements that the department deems necessary to carry out the provisions of
38 this section.
39 (9) The department may adopt rules necessary to manage the cost, size and growth rate of the
40 program described in this section that are necessary to protect the eligibility for and levels of ser-
41 vices under programs serving individuals receiving developmental disability services provided for in
42 the state plan, including the development of criteria to limit the number of children eligible to par-
43 ticipate in the program.
44 (10) Annually, the department shall report to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly
45 related to human services or, if the Legislative Assembly is in session, to the committees of the
[12]

HB 4040
1 Legislative Assembly related to human services, in the manner provided in ORS 192.245, updates on
2 the program described in this section, including:
3 (a) The number of client children receiving attendant care services, the number of children re-
4 ceiving the services from parent providers and the number of children receiving the services from
5 nonparent caregivers;
6 (b) The number of hours of attendant care services provided by parent providers and number
7 of hours of attendant care services provided by nonparent caregivers;
8 (c) A comparison of the cost per child of providing attendant care services by parent providers
9 under the program with the cost per child of providing attendant care services by nonparent
10 caregivers; and
11 (d) A report on the adequacy of the direct care workforce in this state to provide services to
