36 SECTION 42. ORS 475A.372 is amended to read:
37 475A.372. (1) As used in this section, “adverse behavioral reaction” and “adverse medical re-
38 action” have the meanings given those terms by rule by the Oregon Health Authority.
39 (2) A psilocybin service center operator that holds a license issued under ORS 475A.305 shall:
40 (a) Collect and maintain the following information, in addition to the information required to
41 complete a client information form described in ORS 475A.350:
42 (A) The race, ethnicity, preferred spoken and written languages, disability status, sexual orien-
43 tation, gender identity, income, age, veteran status and county of residence of each client; and
44 (B) The reasons for which a client requests psilocybin services;
45 (b) Compile and maintain the following information that pertains to the three-month period im-
[32]

HB 4040
1 mediately preceding a quarterly submission under subsection (4) of this section:
2 (A) The number of clients served;
3 (B) The number of individual administration sessions provided;
4 (C) The number of group administration sessions provided;
5 (D) The number of individuals to whom the psilocybin service center or a psilocybin service
6 facilitator practicing at the psilocybin service center denied psilocybin services and the reasons for
7 which psilocybin services were denied;
8 (E) The number and severity of:
9 (i) Adverse behavioral reactions experienced by clients, of which the psilocybin service center
10 operator is aware; and
11 (ii) Adverse medical reactions experienced by clients, of which the psilocybin service center
12 operator is aware; and
13 (F) Any additional information required by the authority by rule as described in subsection (7)
14 of this section; and
15 (c) Compute, for the period described in paragraph (b) of this subsection, and maintain the fol-
16 lowing information:
17 (A) The average number of times per client that psilocybin services were received;
18 (B) The average number of clients participating in each group administration session; [and]
19 (C) For doses higher than five milligrams of psilocybin analyte, the total average dose of
20 psilocybin per client per administration session[.]; and
21 (D) For doses of five milligrams or less of psilocybin analyte, the total average dose of
22 psilocybin per client per administration session.
23 (3) Pursuant to rules adopted by the authority, a client may request that a psilocybin service
24 center operator not submit to the authority information provided by the client as described in sub-
25 section (2) of this section.
26 (4) Subject to subsection (3) of this section, a psilocybin service center operator shall aggregate
27 and submit, in a manner that protects the personally identifiable information of a client or individual
28 from whom information is collected, to the authority on a quarterly basis the information described
29 in subsection (2) of this section. The authority may exempt from the submission requirement infor-
30 mation that the authority determines cannot be adequately deidentified.
31 (5) The authority shall submit the information received under subsection (4) of this section to
32 the Oregon Health and Science University for the purpose of enabling the evaluation of outcomes
33 of psilocybin services provided under ORS 475A.210 to 475A.722.
34 (6)(a) Except as otherwise required by law, the information collected, maintained and reported
35 under this section is exempt from disclosure under ORS 192.311 to 192.478.
36 (b) Information collected, computed, maintained or reported under this section may not be sold.
37 (7) The authority may adopt rules to carry out this section. Rules adopted under this section
38 may include rules to require a psilocybin service center operator to collect and submit to the au-
39 thority information in addition to that described in subsection (2) of this section that, in the dis-
40 cretion of the authority, would be beneficial to understanding the outcomes of psilocybin services
41 provided under ORS 475A.210 to 475A.722.
