15 656.268. (1) One purpose of this chapter is to restore the injured worker as soon as possible and
16 as near as possible to a condition of self support and maintenance as an able-bodied worker. The
17 insurer or self-insured employer shall close the worker’s claim, as prescribed by the Director of the
18 Department of Consumer and Business Services, and determine the extent of the worker’s permanent
19 disability, provided the worker is not enrolled and actively engaged in training according to rules
20 adopted by the director pursuant to ORS 656.340 and 656.726, when one of the following conditions
21 is met:
22 (a) The worker has become medically stationary and there is sufficient information to determine
23 permanent disability. Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, a physician [or nurse
24 practitioner] may not retroactively determine a worker to be medically stationary more than 60 days
25 prior to the date of the determination except in the case of claims that are subject to subsection (13)
26 of this section. An insurer or self-insured employer must mail or deliver written notice to a worker
27 and to the worker’s attorney, if the worker is represented, within seven days following receipt of
28 information that the worker is medically stationary.
29 (b) The accepted injury is no longer the major contributing cause of the worker’s combined or
30 consequential condition or conditions pursuant to ORS 656.005 (7). When the claim is closed because
31 the accepted injury is no longer the major contributing cause of the worker’s combined or conse-
32 quential condition or conditions, and there is sufficient information to determine permanent disabil-
33 ity, the likely permanent disability that would have been due to the current accepted condition shall
34 be estimated.
35 (c) Without the approval of the attending physician [or nurse practitioner authorized to provide
36 compensable medical services under ORS 656.245], the worker fails to seek medical treatment for a
37 period of 30 days or the worker fails to attend a closing examination, unless the worker
38 affirmatively establishes that such failure is attributable to reasons beyond the worker’s control.
39 (d) An insurer or self-insured employer finds that a worker who has been receiving permanent
40 total disability benefits has materially improved and is capable of regularly performing work at a
