HB 4040
1 SECTION 57. ORS 656.325 is amended to read:
2 656.325. (1)(a) Any worker entitled to receive compensation under this chapter is required, if
3 requested by the Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services, the insurer or
4 self-insured employer, to submit to a medical examination at a time reasonably convenient for the
5 worker as may be provided by the rules of the director. No more than three independent medical
6 examinations may be requested except after notification to and authorization by the director. If the
7 worker refuses to submit to any such examination, or obstructs the same, the rights of the worker
8 to compensation shall be suspended with the consent of the director until the examination has taken
9 place, and no compensation shall be payable during or for account of such period. The provisions
10 of this paragraph are subject to the limitations on medical examinations provided in ORS 656.268.
11 (b) When a worker is requested by the director, the insurer or self-insured employer to attend
12 an independent medical examination, the examination must be conducted by a physician selected
13 from a list of qualified physicians established by the director under ORS 656.328.
14 (c) The director shall adopt rules applicable to independent medical examinations conducted
15 pursuant to paragraph (a) of this subsection that:
16 (A) Provide a worker the opportunity to request review by the director of the reasonableness
17 of the location selected for an independent medical examination. Upon receipt of the request for
18 review, the director shall conduct an expedited review of the location selected for the independent
19 medical examination and issue an order on the reasonableness of the location of the examination.
20 The director shall determine if there is substantial evidence for the objection to the location for the
21 independent medical examination based on a conclusion that the required travel is medically
22 contraindicated or other good cause establishing that the required travel is unreasonable. The de-
23 terminations of the director about the location of independent medical examinations are not subject
24 to review.
25 (B) Impose a monetary penalty against a worker who fails to attend an independent medical
26 examination without prior notification or without justification for not attending the examination. A
27 penalty imposed under this subparagraph may be imposed only on a worker who is not receiving
28 temporary disability benefits under ORS 656.210 or 656.212. An insurer or self-insured employer may
29 offset any future compensation payable to the worker to recover any penalty imposed under this
30 subparagraph from a claim with the same insurer or self-insured employer. When a penalty is re-
31 covered from temporary disability or permanent total disability benefits, the amount recovered from
32 each payment may not exceed 25 percent of the benefit payment without prior authorization from
33 the worker.
34 (C) Impose a sanction against a medical service provider that unreasonably fails to provide in
35 a timely manner diagnostic records required for an independent medical examination.
36 (d) Notwithstanding ORS 656.262 (6), if the director determines that the location selected for an
37 independent medical examination is unreasonable, the insurer or self-insured employer shall accept
38 or deny the claim within 90 days after the employer has notice or knowledge of the claim.
39 (e) If the worker has made a timely request for a hearing on a denial of compensability as re-
40 quired by ORS 656.319 (1)(a) that is based on one or more reports of examinations conducted pur-
41 suant to paragraph (a) of this subsection and the worker’s attending physician [or nurse practitioner
42 authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] does not concur with the re-
43 port or reports, the worker may request an examination to be conducted by a physician selected by
44 the director from the list described in ORS 656.328. The cost of the examination and the examination
45 report shall be paid by the insurer or self-insured employer.
