41 (4) The director hereby is charged with duties of administration, regulation and enforcement of
42 ORS 654.001 to 654.295, 654.412 to 654.423, 654.750 to 654.780 and this chapter. To that end the di-
43 rector may:
44 (a) Make and declare all rules and issue orders which are reasonably required in the perform-
45 ance of the director’s duties. Unless otherwise specified by law, all reports, claims or other docu-
[69]

HB 4040
1 ments shall be deemed timely provided to the director or board if mailed by regular mail or
2 delivered within the time required by law. Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, the
3 director may adopt rules to allow for the electronic transmission and filing of reports, claims or
4 other documents required to be filed under this chapter and to require the electronic transmission
5 and filing of proof of coverage required under ORS 656.419, 656.423 and 656.427. Notwithstanding
6 ORS 183.310 to 183.410, if a matter comes before the director that is not addressed by rule and the
7 director finds that adoption of a rule to accommodate the matter would be inefficient, unreasonable
8 or unnecessarily burdensome to the public, the director may resolve the matter by issuing an order,
9 subject to review under ORS 656.704. Such order shall not have precedential effect as to any other
10 situation.
11 (b) Hold sessions at any place within the state.
12 (c) Administer oaths.
13 (d) Issue and serve by representatives of the director, or by any sheriff, subpoenas for the at-
14 tendance of witnesses and the production of papers, contracts, books, accounts, documents and tes-
15 timony in any inquiry, investigation, proceeding or rulemaking hearing conducted by the director
16 or the director’s representatives. The director may require the attendance and testimony of em-
17 ployers, their officers and representatives in any inquiry under this chapter, and the production by
18 employers of books, records, papers and documents without the payment or tender of witness fees
19 on account of such attendance.
20 (e) Generally provide for the taking of testimony and for the recording of such proceedings.
21 (f) Provide standards for the evaluation of disabilities. The following provisions apply to the
22 standards:
23 (A) The criterion for evaluation of permanent impairment under ORS 656.214 is the loss of use
24 or function of a body part or system due to the compensable industrial injury or occupational dis-
25 ease. Permanent impairment is expressed as a percentage of the whole person. The impairment value
26 may not exceed 100 percent of the whole person.
27 (B) Impairment is established by a preponderance of medical evidence based upon objective
28 findings.
29 (C) The criterion for evaluation of work disability under ORS 656.214 is permanent impairment
30 as modified by the factors of age, education and adaptability to perform a given job.
31 (D) When, upon reconsideration of a notice of closure pursuant to ORS 656.268, it is found that
32 the worker’s disability is not addressed by the standards adopted pursuant to this paragraph,
33 notwithstanding ORS 656.268, the director shall, in the order on reconsideration, determine the ex-
34 tent of permanent disability that addresses the worker’s impairment.
35 (E) Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, only impairment benefits shall be
36 awarded under ORS 656.214 if the worker has been released to regular work by the attending phy-
37 sician [or nurse practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245]
38 or has returned to regular work at the job held at the time of injury.
39 (g) Prescribe procedural rules for and conduct hearings, investigations and other proceedings
40 pursuant to ORS 654.001 to 654.295, 654.412 to 654.423, 654.750 to 654.780 and this chapter regarding
41 all matters other than those specifically allocated to the board or the Hearings Division.
42 (h) Participate fully in any proceeding before the Hearings Division, board or Court of Appeals
43 in which the director determines that the proceeding involves a matter that affects or could affect
44 the discharge of the director’s duties of administration, regulation and enforcement of ORS 654.001
45 to 654.295, 654.412 to 654.423, 654.750 to 654.780 and this chapter.
[70]

HB 4040
1 (5)(a) The board may make and declare all rules which are reasonably required in the perform-
2 ance of its duties, including but not limited to rules of practice and procedure in connection with
3 hearing and review proceedings and exercising its authority under ORS 656.278. The board shall
4 adopt standards governing the format and timing of the evidence. The standards shall be uniformly
5 followed by all Administrative Law Judges and practitioners. The rules may provide for informal
6 prehearing conferences in order to expedite claim adjudication, amicably dispose of controversies,
7 if possible, narrow issues and simplify the method of proof at hearings. The rules shall specify who
8 may appear with parties at prehearing conferences and hearings.
9 (b) Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter, the board may adopt rules to allow for
10 the electronic transmission of filings, reports, notices and other documents required to be filed under
11 the board’s authority.
12 (6) The director and the board chairperson may incur such expenses as they respectively de-
13 termine are reasonably necessary to perform their authorized functions.
14 (7) The director, the board chairperson and the State Accident Insurance Fund Corporation shall
15 have the right, not subject to review, to contract for the exchange of, or payment for, such services
16 between them as will reduce the overall cost of administering this chapter.
17 (8) The director shall have lien and enforcement powers regarding assessments to be paid by
18 subject employers in the same manner and to the same extent as is provided for lien and enforce-
19 ment of collection of premiums and assessments by the corporation under ORS 656.552 to 656.566.
20 (9) The director shall have the same powers regarding inspection of books, records and payrolls
21 of employers as are granted the corporation under ORS 656.758. The director may disclose infor-
22 mation obtained from such inspections to the Director of the Department of Revenue to the extent
23 the Director of the Department of Revenue requires such information to determine that a person
24 complies with the revenue and tax laws of this state and to the Director of the Employment De-
25 partment to the extent the Director of the Employment Department requires such information to
26 determine that a person complies with ORS chapter 657.
27 (10) The director shall collect hours-worked data information in addition to total payroll for
28 workers engaged in various jobs in the construction industry classifications described in the job
29 classification portion of the Workers’ Compensation and Employers Liability Manual and the Oregon
30 Special Rules Section published by the National Council on Compensation Insurance. The informa-
31 tion shall be collected in the form and format necessary for the National Council on Compensation
32 Insurance to analyze premium equity.
33 SECTION 60. ORS 656.797 is amended to read:
34 656.797. On or after October 1, 2004, prior to providing compensable medical services or
35 authorizing temporary disability benefits, a nurse practitioner licensed under ORS 678.375 to
36 678.390[, prior to providing compensable medical services or authorizing temporary disability benefits
37 under ORS 656.245,] must certify in a form acceptable to the Director of the Department of Con-
38 sumer and Business Services that the nurse practitioner has reviewed the materials developed under
39 ORS 656.795.
40 SECTION 61. ORS 659A.043 is amended to read:
41 659A.043. (1) A worker who has sustained a compensable injury shall be reinstated by the
42 worker’s employer to the worker’s former position of employment upon demand for such rein-
43 statement, if the position exists and is available and the worker is not disabled from performing the
44 duties of such position. A worker’s former position is available even if that position has been filled
45 by a replacement while the injured worker was absent. If the former position is not available, the
[71]

HB 4040
1 worker shall be reinstated in any other existing position that is vacant and suitable. A certificate
2 by the attending physician, as defined in ORS 656.005 (12), [or a nurse practitioner authorized to
3 provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] that the attending physician [or nurse
4 practitioner] approves the worker’s return to the worker’s regular employment or other suitable
5 employment shall be prima facie evidence that the worker is able to perform such duties.
6 (2) Such right of reemployment shall be subject to the provisions for seniority rights and other
7 employment restrictions contained in a valid collective bargaining agreement between the employer
8 and a representative of the employer’s employees.
9 (3) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section:
10 (a) The right to reinstatement to the worker’s former position under this section terminates
11 when whichever of the following events first occurs:
12 [(A) A medical determination by the attending physician or, after an appeal of such determination
13 to a medical arbiter or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656, has been made that the
14 worker cannot return to the former position of employment.]
15 (A) The worker cannot return to the former position of employment according to:
16 (i) The medical determination of the attending physician; or
17 (ii) Upon appeal of the attending physician’s determination, the determination of a med-
18 ical arbiter or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656.
19 (B) The worker is eligible and participates in vocational assistance under ORS 656.340.
20 (C) The worker accepts suitable employment with another employer after becoming medically
21 stationary.
22 (D) The worker refuses a bona fide offer from the employer of light duty or modified employment
23 that is suitable prior to becoming medically stationary.
24 (E) Seven days elapse from the date that the worker is notified by the insurer or self-insured
25 employer by certified mail that the worker’s attending physician [or a nurse practitioner authorized
26 to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] has released the worker for employment
27 unless the worker requests reinstatement within that time period.
28 (F) Three years elapse from the date of injury.
29 (b) The right to reinstatement under this section does not apply to:
30 (A) A worker hired on a temporary basis as a replacement for an injured worker.
31 (B) A seasonal worker employed to perform less than six months’ work in a calendar year.
32 (C) A worker whose employment at the time of injury resulted from referral from a hiring hall
33 operating pursuant to a collective bargaining agreement.
34 (D) A worker whose employer employs 20 or fewer workers at the time of the worker’s injury
35 and at the time of the worker’s demand for reinstatement.
36 (4) Notwithstanding ORS 659A.165, a worker who refuses an offer of employment under sub-
37 section (3)(a)(D) of this section and who otherwise is entitled to family leave under ORS 659A.150
38 to 659A.186:
39 (a) Automatically commences a period of family leave under ORS 659A.150 to 659A.186 upon
40 refusing the offer of employment; and
41 (b) Need not give additional written or oral notice to the employer that the employee is com-
42 mencing a period of family leave.
43 (5) Any violation of this section is an unlawful employment practice.
44 SECTION 62. ORS 659A.046 is amended to read:
45 659A.046. (1) A worker who has sustained a compensable injury and is disabled from performing
[72]

HB 4040
1 the duties of the worker’s former regular employment shall, upon demand, be reemployed by the
2 worker’s employer at employment which is available and suitable.
3 (2) A certificate of the worker’s attending physician, as defined in ORS 656.005 (12), [or a nurse
4 practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] that the worker
5 is able to perform described types of work shall be prima facie evidence of such ability.
6 (3) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, the right to reemployment under this section
7 terminates when whichever of the following events first occurs:
8 [(a) The worker cannot return to reemployment at any position with the employer either by deter-
9 mination of the attending physician or a nurse practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical
10 services under ORS 656.245 or upon appeal of that determination, by determination of a medical arbiter
11 or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656.]
12 (a) The worker cannot return to reemployment at any position with the employer ac-
13 cording to:
14 (A) The determination of the attending physician; or
15 (B) Upon appeal of the attending physician’s determination, the determination of a med-
16 ical arbiter or panel of medical arbiters pursuant to ORS chapter 656.
17 (b) The worker is eligible and participates in vocational assistance under ORS 656.340.
18 (c) The worker accepts suitable employment with another employer after becoming medically
19 stationary.
20 (d) The worker refuses a bona fide offer from the employer of light duty or modified employment
21 that is suitable prior to becoming medically stationary.
22 (e) Seven days elapse from the date that the worker is notified by the insurer or self-insured
23 employer by certified mail that the worker’s attending physician [or a nurse practitioner authorized
24 to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] has released the worker for reemploy-
25 ment unless the worker requests reemployment within that time period.
26 (f) Three years elapse from the date of injury.
27 (4) Such right of reemployment shall be subject to the provisions for seniority rights and other
28 employment restrictions contained in a valid collective bargaining agreement between the employer
29 and a representative of the employer’s employees.
30 (5) Notwithstanding ORS 659A.165, a worker who refuses an offer of employment under sub-
31 section (3)(d) of this section and who otherwise is entitled to family leave under ORS 659A.150 to
32 659A.186:
33 (a) Automatically commences a period of family leave under ORS 659A.150 to 659A.186 upon
34 refusing the offer of employment; and
35 (b) Need not give additional written or oral notice to the employer that the employee is com-
36 mencing a period of family leave.
37 (6) Any violation of this section is an unlawful employment practice.
38 (7) This section applies only to employers who employ six or more persons.
39 SECTION 63. ORS 659A.049 is amended to read:
40 659A.049. The rights of reinstatement and reemployment afforded by ORS 659A.043 and
41 659A.046 shall not be forfeited if the worker refuses to return to the worker’s regular or other of-
42 fered employment without release to such employment by the worker’s attending physician as de-
43 fined in ORS 656.005 (12) [or a nurse practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services
44 under ORS 656.245].
45 SECTION 64. ORS 659A.063 is amended to read:
[73]

HB 4040
1 659A.063. (1) The State of Oregon shall cause group health benefits to continue in effect with
2 respect to that worker and any covered dependents or family members by timely payment of the
3 premium that includes the contribution due from the state under the applicable benefit plan, subject
4 to any premium contribution due from the worker that the worker paid before the occurrence of the
5 injury or illness. If the premium increases or decreases, the State of Oregon and worker contribu-
6 tions shall be adjusted to remain consistent with similarly situated active employees. The State of
7 Oregon shall continue the worker’s health benefits in effect until whichever of the following events
8 occurs first:
9 (a) The worker’s attending physician as defined in ORS 656.005 (12) [or a nurse practitioner
10 authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] has determined the worker
11 to be medically stationary and a notice of closure has been entered;
12 (b) The worker returns to work for the State of Oregon, after a period of continued coverage
13 under this section, and satisfies any probationary or minimum work requirement to be eligible for
14 group health benefits;
15 (c) The worker takes full- or part-time employment with another employer that is comparable in
16 terms of the number of hours per week the worker was employed with the State of Oregon or the
17 worker retires;
18 (d) Twelve months have elapsed since the date the State of Oregon received notice that the
19 worker filed a workers’ compensation claim pursuant to ORS chapter 656;
20 (e) The claim is denied and the claimant fails to appeal within the time provided by ORS 656.319
21 or the Workers’ Compensation Board or a workers’ compensation hearings referee or a court issues
22 an order finding the claim is not compensable;
23 (f) The worker does not pay the required premium or portion thereof in a timely manner in ac-
24 cordance with the terms and conditions under this section;
25 (g) The worker elects to discontinue coverage under this section and notifies the State of
26 Oregon in writing of this election;
27 (h) The worker’s attending physician [or a nurse practitioner authorized to provide compensable
28 medical services under ORS 656.245] has released the worker to modified or regular work, the work
29 has been offered to the worker and the worker refuses to return to work; or
30 (i) The worker has been terminated from employment for reasons unrelated to the workers’
31 compensation claim.
32 (2) If the workers’ compensation claim of a worker for whom health benefits are provided pur-
33 suant to subsection (1) of this section is denied and the worker does not appeal or the worker ap-
34 peals and does not prevail, the State of Oregon may recover from the worker the amount of the
35 premiums plus interest at the rate authorized by ORS 82.010. The State of Oregon may recover the
36 payments through a payroll deduction not to exceed 10 percent of gross pay for each pay period.
37 (3) The State of Oregon shall notify the worker of the provisions of ORS 659A.060 to 659A.069,
38 and of the remedies available for breaches of ORS 659A.060 to 659A.069, within a reasonable time
39 after the State of Oregon receives notice that the worker will be absent from work as a result of
40 an injury or illness for which a workers’ compensation claim has been filed pursuant to ORS chapter
41 656. The notice from the State of Oregon shall include the terms and conditions of the continuation
42 of health benefits and what events will terminate the coverage.
43 (4) If the worker fails to make timely payment of any premium contribution owing, the State of
44 Oregon shall notify the worker of impending cancellation of the health benefits and provide the
45 worker with 30 days to pay the required premium prior to canceling the policy.
[74]

HB 4040
1 (5) It is an unlawful employment practice for the State of Oregon to discriminate against a
2 worker, as defined in ORS 659A.060, by terminating the worker’s group health benefits while that
3 worker is absent from the place of employment as a result of an injury or illness for which a
4 workers’ compensation claim has been filed pursuant to ORS chapter 656, except as provided for in
5 this section.
6 SECTION 65. ORS 657.170 is amended to read:
7 657.170. (1) If the Director of the Employment Department finds that during the base year of the
8 individual any individual has been incapable of work during the greater part of any calendar quar-
9 ter, such base year shall be extended a calendar quarter. Except as provided in subsection (2) of
10 this section, no such extension of an individual’s base year shall exceed four calendar quarters.
11 (2) If the director finds that during and prior to the individual’s base year the individual has
12 had a period of temporary total disability caused by illness or injury and has received compensation
13 under ORS chapter 656 for a period of temporary total disability during the greater part of any
14 calendar quarter, the individual’s base year shall be extended as many calendar quarters as neces-
15 sary to establish a valid claim, up to a maximum of four calendar quarters prior to the quarter in
16 which the illness or injury occurred, if the individual:
17 (a) Files a claim for benefits not later than the fourth calendar week of unemployment following
18 whichever is the latest of the following dates:
19 (A) The date the individual is released to return to work by the attending physician[, as defined
20 in ORS chapter 656, or a nurse practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under
21 ORS 656.245] as defined in ORS 656.005 (12); or
22 (B) The date of mailing of a notice of claim closure pursuant to ORS chapter 656; and
23 (b) Files such a claim within the three-year period immediately following the commencement of
24 such period of illness or injury.
25 (3) Notwithstanding the provisions of this section, benefits payable as a result of the use of
26 wages paid in a calendar quarter prior to the individual’s current base year shall not exceed one-
27 third of such wages less benefits paid previously as a result of the use of such wages in computing
28 a previous benefit determination.
